Vegetarian or vegan? Go find another excuse. 

Protein is not optional — especially if you care about fat loss, strong hair and nails, smooth skin, better recovery, and aging well.

But here’s the good news:
You don’t need to force down the same boring grilled tofu or plain paneer every single day. You just need a better way to use them.

🥄 Tofu can be scrambled, blended into a sauce, added to broths, grilled on skewers, even baked into snacks.

🧀 Paneer? My favorite dip base. Stuff it, sauté it, or blend it with spices. You’ll never look at it the same.

Most people struggle not because they lack options — but because they lack inspiration.

I create recipes and nutrition strategies that help women eat better without feeling bored, restricted, or overwhelmed. If you’re vegetarian or vegan and trying to eat more protein, this page is for you.

Still stuck — despite doing everything “right”? Prolactin might be the hormone no one told you to check.

You’re eating clean. You’re working out consistently.
You’ve said no to cake more times than you can count.
But the scale won’t move… your energy is low… and your body just feels off.

Sound familiar?

It might not be your routine — it might be your prolactin levels.

🧬 Prolactin is a hormone that’s supposed to help with things like breastfeeding.

But in many women — especially those with PCOS, chronic stress, or undergoing IVF/IUI — it stays elevated when it shouldn’t. And when prolactin is high? It makes weight loss feel impossible.

Here’s what it can do:
• Slows down metabolism
• Disrupts ovulation and periods
• Increases stubborn fat around belly + hips
• Raises cravings (especially for carbs/sugar)
• Causes fatigue, low motivation, even mood dips
• Impacts thyroid and estrogen levels indirectly
• Makes you feel like your body is stuck — no matter how “healthy” you are

And most women have no idea it’s happening — because no one tells them to test for it.

You’re not crazy. You’re not lazy. You’re not broken.
You’re just missing a piece of the hormone puzzle.

✨ In my next reel, I’m breaking down exactly what you can do to start lowering elevated prolactin — and how to support your body the right way.

Ever feel like a totally different human the week before your period?
Bloated, irritable, craving junk, emotionally ✨fragile✨ for no reason?

Yeah, that’s the second part of your luteal phase — and it’s not in your head. It’s in your hormones.

🧠 Here’s what’s happening:
After ovulation, your progesterone rises to support a possible pregnancy.
But if that doesn’t happen, both progesterone and estrogen drop sharply — and that hormonal crash affects everything from mood to digestion.

👀 What you might feel:
• Cravings that don’t make sense
• Sluggish digestion or random bloating
• Energy dips + low motivation
• Mood swings, irritation, or feeling low
• Sleep disruptions (yes, even if you’re tired)

✨ What helps:
• Focus on protein + slow carbs to support blood sugar
• Magnesium-rich foods (leafy greens, dark chocolate, pumpkin seeds)
• Go gentler with workouts — your body’s more inflamed
• Hydrate + reduce salty, packaged foods
• Give yourself permission to rest — your hormones are shifting gears

This phase isn’t about pushing through — it’s about working with your body, not against it.
Follow me if you want to feel better, not just powered through. 💛

#HormoneHealth

Monday used to be my least favorite day. Not because I wasn’t motivated. But because I felt like I was always starting from scratch. New week, new pressure.
Eat clean. Be disciplined. Say no. It felt like a punishment — not a rhythm. And by 4pm, I was usually dreaming of something sweet.

So this time, I changed my approach. I removed the bread from breakfast. Kept my scramble high in protein and fat. Lunch was basic but functional. I crushed my gym session. I chose a clean, satisfying dinner.
And then? I gave myself a treat.

Not because I messed up — but because I stuck with it.
No chaos. No guilt. Just something small to say, “you did good today.” That made all the difference.
